results.notes:
Multiple groups of this species have emerged recently following modest mid-Nov rain followed by not-too-cold temperatures during the day. Observing in leaf litter under live oaks (but with gray pines in vicinity) in groups of up to half a dozen within a several-foot radius. Steely gray cap with prominent striations at margins and usually with white universal veil patch in center. One specimen (see images) was at an earlier stage and gray cap was barely visible at periphery of veil patch.

When posted similar in 2015, experts opined Amanita pachycolea or Amanita sect. Vaginitae sensu Zhu L. Yang. Welcome current take of experts; could obtain additional pics of necessary.

results.notes: Found in grassy skirt at the edge of Douglas fir and oak forest. In some ways it looks like a standard Russula brevipes. But the stem is longer than I’ve seen in other pictures and in the field. The gills are also not white. But I understand later in the life of the fruit body, the gills will often take the color of the spores. Still, the cap had some interesting hues of yellow and red around its edge. Not sure if this would also be attributable to age.

results.notes:
Fruiting in needle litter(base attached to needles) beneath Douglas fir and Western red cedar. Did not note any Pacific Yew in vicinity.
Fruiting bodies translucent, waxy in appearance with corona like wavy margin. Stem bases staining faintly red where handled.
Harvested 4 specimens.
Laying all specimens directly on a glass slide to obtain spore drop.
Spore print: White.
Mounted spore printed slide in Lugol’s solution.
Spores: Subglobose to globose, very small. Greenish yellow to faintly blue in Lugol’s solution. Weakly amyloid.
Slide#2: carefully shaved a thin section of fertile tissue with straight razor and mounted directly on slide#2. Mounted tissue in KOH.
Basidia: 2 and 4 sterigmate analyzed.
Gloeocystidia: long, slender, very slightly clavate tips.
Dehydrated all specimens thoroughly and bagged for herbarium collection/genetic record.

(Psilocybe liniformans)
Named after the edge of the blades which bears a detachable gelina with a fine tweezer, characteristic of the species, thus drastically differentiating it from other coprophilous and subcoprophilic species of the semilanceata group (in particular P. fimetaria).
Two very distinct morphotypes are present in equal proportion on the inventory site.
One is topped with a very pointed nipple which may suggest a P. fimetaria without an annular zone (or even a P. semilaceata), the other does not have one at all, bringing it morphologically closer to the Deconica group. coprophiles and subcoprophiles.
Ecology: on the ground in the blueberry bushes, in the undergrowth of conifer mixed with beech, adjoining a natural hydromorphic pasture.
It grows directly on cow dung or horse droppings which have dried in the summer and then taken a very long time the cool rains of the autumn season.
Description: macroscopically it closely resembles P. fimetaria, but without the annular zone.
The gelin detachable from the lamellae is present on all samples.
The very numerous cheilocistydes are very diverticulated (bifid, shaped like deer antlers).

Comments: Russula aurea is a widespread but not common brittlegill, having a vividly colored and beautiful sporocarps. The name Russula means red or reddish. This is because many of the huge number of species in this genus have red cups. It is typical for this species to show a mixture of yellow, orange and red tints. It is a mild-tasting and edible mushroom, but it is unusual to find them in a sufficient number to justify collecting. It grows mainly under hardwood trees, particularly under beech (Fagus sylvatica), but also under conifers (Ref.3). A vertical section revealed only a featureless dusky pink mass encased in a thin pale cortex. The exposed surface of the section did not scrape away nor mar easily.
